---
import DocsLayout from '@/layouts/DocsLayout.astro'
---
<DocsLayout
  title="Blue-Green Deploy"
  description="Zero-downtime deployments using two live slots, with atomic proxy swap and automatic rollback."
  section="strategies"
>
  <p>
    Blue-green is Shuttle's default deploy strategy. Two container slots — <strong>blue</strong> and
    <strong>green</strong> — alternate on each deploy. The new version starts in the idle slot, passes
    health checks, then the proxy atomically switches traffic. The old slot drains and stops only after
    traffic has moved away.
  </p>

  <h2>Port assignment</h2>
  <p>
    Ports are deterministic and never collide across services. For a service at index <code>i</code>:
  </p>
  <ul>
    <li>Blue slot port: <code>10000 + i * 2</code></li>
    <li>Green slot port: <code>10000 + i * 2 + 1</code></li>
  </ul>
  <p>
    For a single-service app the blue slot listens on <code>10000</code> and green on
    <code>10001</code>. A second service would use <code>10002</code> / <code>10003</code>, and so on.
    Ports are bound to <code>127.0.0.1</code> only — they are never exposed publicly; Caddy proxies
    inbound traffic.
  </p>

  <h2>12-step deploy pipeline</h2>
  <ol>
    <li><strong>Read deployment state</strong> — load <code>state.json</code> from <code>/opt/shuttle/&lt;app&gt;/</code> to determine the currently active slot.</li>
    <li><strong>Generate image tag</strong> — format: <code>shuttle/&lt;app&gt;:deploy-YYYYMMDD-&lt;shortsha&gt;</code>.</li>
    <li><strong>Build &amp; transfer image</strong> — build locally with <code>docker build</code>, then send to the server via the configured registry provider (default: <code>docker save | ssh docker load</code>). Skipped with <code>--skip-build</code>.</li>
    <li><strong>Transfer image</strong> — upload the saved tarball over SSH. Skipped with <code>--skip-build</code>.</li>
    <li><strong>Upload environment</strong> — push AES-encrypted secrets as <code>.env</code> (mode <code>0600</code>) to <code>/opt/shuttle/&lt;app&gt;/&lt;app&gt;/.env</code>.</li>
    <li><strong>Start new container</strong> — <code>docker run</code> on the new slot port, bound to <code>127.0.0.1</code>.</li>
    <li><strong>Wait for health check</strong> — poll the health check endpoint (http, tcp, or exec) up to the configured retries. Applies <code>readiness_delay</code> before the first probe. On failure, the new container is stopped and the error is surfaced.</li>
    <li><strong>Switch proxy upstream</strong> — Caddy's admin API atomically repoints the upstream to the new slot port. Zero connections are dropped.</li>
    <li><strong>Update deployment state</strong> — write <code>state.json</code> with the new slot, tag, port, and incremented version counter.</li>
    <li><strong>Drain old container</strong> — send <code>SIGTERM</code> to the old container, wait up to <code>drain_timeout</code> seconds (default: 30s), then <code>docker stop</code>.</li>
    <li><strong>Tag images</strong> — tag the new image as <code>shuttle/&lt;app&gt;:current</code> and the previous as <code>shuttle/&lt;app&gt;:previous</code>.</li>
    <li><strong>Prune old images</strong> — remove deploy-tagged images beyond the <code>retain</code> count (default: 3).</li>
  </ol>

  <h2>Flow diagram</h2>
  <pre><code>
  BEFORE DEPLOY              DURING DEPLOY              AFTER DEPLOY
  ─────────────              ─────────────              ────────────
  Internet                   Internet                   Internet
     │                          │                          │
  Caddy ──► blue:10000       Caddy ──► blue:10000       Caddy ──► green:10001
                              green:10001 (starting)      blue draining...
  blue: running              blue: running               blue: stopped
  green: stopped             green: healthy              green: running
  </code></pre>

  <h2>Configuration</h2>
  <pre><code class="language-yaml">app: my-app
domain: my-app.example.com

server:
  host: 203.0.113.10
  user: deploy

build:
  dockerfile: Dockerfile

services:
  web:
    command: node server.js
    port: 3000
    healthcheck:
      type: http
      path: /health
      interval: 5
      timeout: 3
      retries: 5

deploy:
  strategy: blue-green          # default — can be omitted
  timeout: 120                  # seconds to wait for health check
  retain: 5                     # deploy images to keep
  auto_rollback: true           # stop new container on health check failure
  blue_green:
    drain_timeout: 30           # seconds to wait for old container to drain
    readiness_delay: 2          # seconds before the first health probe
  hooks:
    pre_deploy:
      - php artisan migrate --force
    post_deploy:
      - php artisan cache:clear
</code></pre>

  <h2>Auto-rollback</h2>
  <p>
    When <code>auto_rollback: true</code> (the default) and the health check fails, Shuttle
    immediately stops the new container before re-throwing the error. The old container is still
    running and serving traffic — Caddy was never switched — so the rollback is instant and
    transparent to users. No manual intervention is needed.
  </p>

  <h2>Caddy atomic reload</h2>
  <p>
    Shuttle uses Caddy's JSON admin API (<code>POST /config/</code>) to update the upstream address.
    Caddy applies the change in-place without restarting, ensuring that long-lived connections (SSE,
    WebSockets) are not interrupted. The switch completes in under 100ms.
  </p>
</DocsLayout>
